# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: david-white-geologist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:david-white-geologist/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:david-white-geologist/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:david-white-geologist/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:david-white-geologist/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:david-white-geologist/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:david-white-geologist/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:david-white-geologist/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:david-white-geologist/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The majority of Americans trace their roots to immigrants who arrived in what is now the United States, starting with European colonization in the 16th century.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] This includes European American groups such as the English, Irish, Germans, Italians, and others, as well as Africans forcibly brought as slaves during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] However, the Native American population, whose ancestors inhabited the continent for thousands of years before European contact, are a key exception.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Despite its multi-ethnic composition, the culture of the United States held in common by most Americans can also be referred to as mainstream American culture — a Western culture largely derived from the traditions of Northern and Western European colonists, settlers, and immigrants.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] It also includes significant influences of African-American culture.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Westward expansion integrated the French-speaking Creoles and Cajuns of Louisiana and the Hispanos of the American Southwest, who brought close contact with the culture of Mexico.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Large-scale immigration in the late 19th and early 20th centuries from Eastern and Southern Europe introduced a variety of new customs.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Immigration from Africa, Asia, and Latin America has also had impact.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] A cultural melting pot, or pluralistic salad bowl, describes the way in which generations of Americans have celebrated and exchanged distinctive cultural characteristics.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The original Indigenous population came to the United States region from Siberia via the Bering Strait.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Various Native American tribes were established in what is now the United States for thousands of years before European colonization and the Native American genocide in the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Estimates suggest that the pre-contact population varied between 3 million and 12 million individuals, residing in over 600 distinct societies.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Each region was home to tribes with unique Indigenous cultures, languages, and ways of life.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The initial European conquerors were from Spain, who had invaded nearby Mexico and the southwestern territories in the late sixteenth century, during which time they enslaved Native American populations.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The French and Dutch colonists made their appearance in the seventeenth century, followed by the British.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The impact of the Europeans was catastrophic, as they introduced and gave previously unknown diseases that decimated entire Native American populations, such as smallpox, syphilis, and influenza.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States is a diverse country, both racially and ethnically.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Six races are officially recognized by the United States Census Bureau for statistical purposes: Alaska Native and American Indian, Asian, Black or African American, Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander, White, and people of two or more races.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] "Some other race" is also an option in the census and other surveys.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States Census Bureau also classifies Americans as "Hispanic or Latino" and "Not Hispanic or Latino", which identifies Hispanic and Latino Americans as a racially diverse *ethnicity* that comprises the largest minority group in the nation.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] White Americans constitute the majority of the 331 million people living in the United States, with 204,277,273 people or 61.6% of the population in the 2020 United States census.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The US census defines "white" as "[a] person having origins in any of the original peoples of Europe, the Middle East, or North Africa".
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Non-Hispanic Whites, which only account for 57.8% of the population, or 191,697,647 people, are the majority in 44 states.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] There are six minority-majority states: California, Texas, Maryland, New Mexico, Nevada, and Hawaii.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In addition, the District of Columbia and the five inhabited U.S. territories have a non-white majority.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The state with the highest percentage of non-Hispanic White Americans is Maine, while the state with the lowest percentage is Hawaii.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Europe is the largest continent that Americans trace their ancestry to, and many claim descent from various European ethnic groups.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The Spaniards were among the first Europeans to establish a continuous presence in what is now the continental United States in 1565 in San Agustín, La Florida then a part of New Spain.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] 1587) in Roanoke Island in present-day North Carolina, was the first child born in the original Thirteen Colonies to English parents.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The Spaniards also established a continuous presence in what over three centuries later would become a possession of the United States with the founding of the city of San Juan, Puerto Rico, in 1521.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Jewish Americans trace their ancestry primarily to Central and Eastern Europe, with smaller numbers from the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Large numbers of Jewish immigrants arrived in the United States during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, fleeing persecution in the Russian Empire and other parts of Eastern Europe.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] They arrived in cities such as New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] However, the English Americans and British Americans demography is considered a serious under-count as they tend to self-report and identify as simply "Americans" (since the introduction of a new "American" category in the 1990 census) due to the length of time they have inhabited America.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] This is highly over-represented in the Upland South, a region that was settled historically by the British.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Overall, as the largest group, European Americans have the lowest poverty rate and the second highest educational attainment levels, median household income, and median personal income of any racial demographic in the nation, second only to Asian Americans in the latter three categories.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Hispanic and Latino Americans constitute the largest ethnic minority in the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] They form the second largest group in the United States, comprising 62,080,044 people or 18.7% of the population according to the 2020 United States census.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Hispanic and Latino Americans are not considered a race in the United States census, instead forming an ethnic category.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] People of Spanish or Hispanic and Latino descent have lived in what is now United States territory since the founding of San Juan, Puerto Rico (the oldest continuously inhabited settlement on American soil) in 1521 by Juan Ponce de León, and the founding of St.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Augustine, Florida (the oldest continuously inhabited settlement in the continental United States) in 1565 by Pedro Menéndez de Avilés.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In the State of Texas, Spaniards first settled the region in the late 1600s and formed a unique cultural group known as Tejanos.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Black and African Americans are citizens and residents of the United States with origins in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the Office of Management and Budget, the grouping includes individuals who self-identify as African American, as well as persons who emigrated from nations in the Caribbean and sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The grouping is thus based on geography, and may contradict or misrepresent an individual's self-identification since not all immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa are "Black".
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Among these racial outliers are persons from Cape Verde, Madagascar, various Arab states, and Hamito-Semitic populations in East Africa and the Sahel, and the Afrikaners of Southern Africa.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] African Americans (also referred to as Black Americans or Afro-Americans, and formerly as American Negroes) are citizens or residents of the United States who have origins in any of the black populations of Africa.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the 2020 United States census, there were 39,940,338 Black and African Americans in the United States, representing 12.4% of the population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Black and African Americans make up the third largest group in the United States, after White and European Americans, and Hispanic and Latino Americans.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The majority of the population (55%) lives in the South; compared to the 2000 United States census, there has also been a decrease of African Americans in the Northeast and Midwest.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Most African Americans are the direct descendants of captives from Central and West Africa, from ancestral populations in countries like Nigeria, Benin, Sierra Leone, Guinea-Bissau, Senegal, and Angola, who survived the slavery era within the boundaries of the present United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As an adjective, the term is usually spelled *African-American*.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The first West African slaves were brought to Jamestown, Virginia in 1619.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The English settlers treated these captives as indentured servants and released them after a number of years.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] This practice was gradually replaced by the system of race-based slavery used in the Caribbean.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] During the revolution, some would serve in the Continental Army or Continental Navy, while others would serve the British Empire in the Ethiopian Regiment, and other units.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] By 1804, the northern states (north of the Mason–Dixon line) had abolished slavery.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] However, slavery would persist in the southern states until the end of the American Civil War and the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to United States Census Bureau data, very few African immigrants self-identify as African American.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] On average, less than 5% of African residents self-reported as "African American" or "Afro-American" on the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The overwhelming majority of African immigrants (~95%) identified instead with their own respective ethnicities.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Self-designation as "African American" or "Afro-American" was highest among individuals from West Africa (4%–9%), and lowest among individuals from Cape Verde, East Africa and Southern Africa (0%–4%).
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] African immigrants may also experience conflict with African Americans.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Another significant population is the Asian American population, comprising 19,618,719 people in 2020, or 5.9% of the United States population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] California is home to 5.6 million Asian Americans, the greatest number in any state.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In Hawaii, Asian Americans make up the highest proportion of the population (57 percent).
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Asian Americans live across the country, yet are heavily urbanized, with significant populations in the Greater Los Angeles Area, New York metropolitan area, and the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States census defines Asian Americans as those with origins to the countries of Central Asia, East Asia, South Asia, and Southeast Asia.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Although Americans with roots in West Asia were once classified as "Asian", they are now excluded from the term in modern census classifications.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The largest sub-groups are immigrants or descendants of immigrants from Cambodia, mainland China, India, Japan, Korea, Laos, Pakistan, the Philippines, Taiwan, Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Asians overall have higher income levels than all other racial groups in the United States, including whites, and the trend appears to be increasing in relation to those groups.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Additionally, Asians have a higher education attainment level than all other racial groups in the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] For better or for worse, the group has been called a model minority.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] While Asian Americans have been in what is now the United States since before the Revolutionary War, relatively large waves of Chinese, Filipino, and Japanese immigration did not begin until the mid-to-late 19th century.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Immigration and significant population growth continue to this day.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Due to a number of factors, Asian Americans have been stereotyped as "perpetual foreigners".
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Middle Eastern Americans and North African Americans are Americans with ancestry from the Middle East and North Africa (MENA).
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the American Jewish Archives and the Arab American National Museum, the first Middle Easterners and North Africans (especially Jews) to arrive in the Americas landed in the late 15th to mid-16th centuries.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Many fled ethnic or ethnoreligious persecution during the Spanish Inquisition.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In 2014, the United States Census Bureau began finalizing the ethnic classification of people of Middle Eastern and North African ("MENA") origins.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the Arab American Institute (AAI), Arab Americans have family origins in each of the 22 Arab League member states.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The groups felt that the earlier "white" designation no longer accurately represents MENA identity, so they successfully lobbied for a distinct categorization.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] This new category would also include Israeli Americans.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The Census Bureau does not currently ask about whether one is Sikh, because it views them as followers of a religion rather than members of an ethnic group, and it does not combine questions concerning religion with race or ethnicity.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As of December 2015, the sampling strata for the new MENA category includes the Census Bureau's working classification of 19 MENA groups, as well as Iranian, Turkish, Armenian, Afghan, Azerbaijani, and Georgian groups.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In January 2018, it was announced that the Census Bureau would not include the grouping in the 2020 census.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the 2020 United States census, there are 2,251,699 people who are Native Americans or Alaska Natives alone; they make up 0.7% of the total population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the Office of Management and Budget (OMB), an "American Indian or Alaska Native" is a person whose ancestry have origins in any of the original peoples of North, Central, or South America.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] 2.3 million individuals who are American Indian or Alaskan Native are multiracial; additionally the plurality of American Indians reside in the Western United States (40.7%).
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Collectively and historically this race has been known by several names; as of 1995, 50% of those who fall within the OMB definition prefer the term "American Indian", 37% prefer "Native American" and the remainder have no preference or prefer a different term altogether.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Among Americans today, levels of Native American ancestry (distinct from Native American identity) differ.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Based on a sample of users of the 23andMe commercial genetic test, genomes of self-reported African Americans averaged to 0.8% Native American ancestry, those of European Americans averaged to 0.18%, and those of Latinos averaged to 18.0%.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Another genetic study focusing on Native American ancestry in the general population found an average of 38% in Latinos, 1% in African Americans, and 0.1% for European American populations, respectively.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Native Americans, whose ancestry is indigenous to the Americas, originally migrated to the two continents between 10,000 and 45,000 years ago.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] These Paleoamericans spread throughout the two continents and evolved into hundreds of distinct cultures during the pre-Columbian era.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Following the first voyage of Christopher Columbus, the European colonization of the Americas began, with St.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Augustine, Florida becoming the first permanent European settlement in the continental United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As defined by the United States Census Bureau and the Office of Management and Budget, Native Hawaiians and other Pacific Islanders are "persons having origins in any of the original peoples of Hawaii, Guam, Samoa, or other Pacific Islands".
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Previously called Asian Pacific American, along with Asian Americans beginning in 1976, this was changed in 1997.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As of the 2020 United States census, there are 622,018 who reside in the United States, and make up 0.2% of the nation's total population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] 14% of the population have at least a bachelor's degree, and 15.1% live in poverty, below the poverty threshold.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As compared to the 2000 United States census, this population grew by 40%; and 71% live in the West; of those over half (52%) live in either Hawaii or California, with no other states having populations greater than 100,000.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States territories in the Pacific also have large Pacific Islander populations such as Guam and the Northern Mariana Islands (Chammoro), and American Samoa (Samoan).
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The largest concentration of Native Hawaiians and other Pacific Islanders, is Honolulu County in Hawaii, and Los Angeles County in the continental United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States has a growing multiracial identity movement, and this group is one of the fastest growing demographics in the country.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Multiracial Americans numbered 7.0 million in 2008, or 2.3% of the population; by the 2020 census the multiracial increased to 13,548,983, or 4.1% of the total population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] They can be any combination of races (White, Black or African American, Asian, American Indian or Alaska Native, Native Hawaiian or other Pacific Islander, "some other race") and ethnicities.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The largest population of Multiracial Americans were those of White and African American descent, with a total of 1,834,212 self-identifying individuals.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Barack Obama, the 44th President of the United States, is multiracial — his mother is white (of English and Irish descent) and his father is black (of Kenyan descent) — though he identifies only as African American.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the 2020 United States census, 8.4% or 27,915,715 Americans chose to self-identify with the "some other race" category, the third most popular option.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The vast majority of this group was Hispanic or Latino.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] A significant portion of the Hispanic and Latino population self-identifies as Mestizo, particularly the Mexican and Central American community.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Mestizo is not a racial category in the United States census, but signifies someone who has both European and American Indian ancestry.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Uncle Sam is a national personification of the United States and sometimes more specifically of the American government, with the first usage of the term dating from the War of 1812.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] He is depicted as a stern elderly white man with white hair and a goatee beard, and dressed in clothing that recalls the design elements of the flag of the United States – for example, typically a top hat with red and white stripes and white stars on a blue band, and red and white striped trousers.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Columbia is a poetic name for the Americas and the feminine personification of the United States of America, made famous by African American poet Phillis Wheatley during the American Revolutionary War in 1776.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] It has inspired the names of many persons, places, objects, institutions, and companies in the Western Hemisphere and beyond, including the District of Columbia, the seat of government of the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] English is the national language and official language of the United States at the federal level.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Additionally, some laws—such as U.S. naturalization requirements—standardize English.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In 2020, about 245 million, or 78% of the population aged five years and older, spoke only English at home.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Spanish, spoken by 13.4% of the population at home, is the second most common language and the most widely taught second language.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Prior to the signing of Executive Order 14224 in March 2025, which declared English the official language of the U.S., some Americans advocated making English the country's official language, as it is in at least 30 out of the 50 states.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Both English and Hawaiian are official languages in Hawaii by state law.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Alaska has declared its 20 Native American languages to be official, along with English.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In South Dakota, both dialects of the Sioux language have been declared official, along with English.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] While neither has an official language, New Mexico has laws providing for the use of both English and Spanish, as Louisiana does for English and French.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Other states, such as California, mandate the publication of Spanish versions of certain government documents.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Several insular territories grant official recognition to their native languages, along with English: Samoan and Chamorro are recognized by American Samoa and Guam, respectively; Carolinian and Chamorro are recognized by the Northern Mariana Islands; Spanish is an official language of Puerto Rico.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Religion in the United States has a high adherence level compared to other developed countries and a diversity in beliefs.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The First Amendment to the country's Constitution prevents the Federal government from making any "law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof".
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Supreme Court has interpreted this as preventing the government from having any authority in religion.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] A majority of Americans report that religion plays a "very important" role in their lives, a proportion unusual among developed countries.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] However, similar to the other nations of the Americas.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Many faiths have flourished in the United States, including both later imports spanning the country's multicultural immigrant heritage, as well as those founded within the country; these have led the United States to become the most religiously diverse country in the world.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States has the world's largest Christian population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The majority of Americans (76%) are Christians, mostly within Protestant and Catholic denominations; these adherents constitute 48% and 23% of the population, respectively.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Other religions include Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, and Judaism, which collectively make up about 4% to 5% of the adult population.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Another 15% of the adult population identifies as having no religious belief or no religious affiliation.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] According to the American Religious Identification Survey, religious belief varies considerably across the country: 59% of Americans living in Western states (the "Unchurched Belt") report a belief in God, yet in the South (the "Bible Belt") the figure is as high as 86%.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Although some individual states retained established religious confessions well into the 19th century, the United States was the first nation to have no official state-endorsed religion.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Modeling the provisions concerning religion within the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom, the framers of the Constitution rejected any religious test for office.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The First Amendment specifically denied the federal government any power to enact any law respecting either an establishment of religion or prohibiting its free exercise, thus protecting any religious organization, institution, or denomination from government interference.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] European Rationalist and Protestant ideals mainly influenced the decision.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Still, it was also a consequence of the pragmatic concerns of minority religious groups and small states that did not want to be under the power or influence of a national religion that did not represent them.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] American culture is primarily a Western culture, but is influenced by Native American, West African, Latin American, East Asian, and Polynesian cultures.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] The United States of America has its own unique social and cultural characteristics, such as dialect, music, arts, social habits, cuisine, and folklore.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Its chief early European influences came from English, Scottish, Welsh, and Irish settlers of colonial America during British rule.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] British culture, due to colonial ties with Britain that spread the English language, legal system and other cultural inheritances, had a formative influence.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Other important influences came from other parts of Europe, especially Germany, France, and Italy.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Original elements also play a strong role, such as Jeffersonian democracy.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Thomas Jefferson's *Notes on the State of Virginia* was perhaps the first influential domestic cultural critique by an American and a reaction to the prevailing European consensus that America's domestic originality was degenerate.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Prevalent ideas and ideals that evolved domestically, such as national holidays, uniquely American sports, military tradition, and innovations in the arts and entertainment give a strong sense of national pride among the population as a whole.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] American culture includes both conservative and liberal elements, scientific and religious competitiveness, political structures, risk taking and free expression, materialist and moral elements.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Despite certain consistent ideological principles (e.g. individualism, egalitarianism, faith in freedom and democracy), the American culture has a variety of expressions due to its geographical scale and demographic diversity.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Americans have migrated to many places around the world, including Argentina, Australia, Brazil, Canada, Chile, China, Costa Rica, France, Germany, Hong Kong, India, Japan, Mexico, New Zealand, Pakistan, the Philippines, South Korea, the United Arab Emirates, and the United Kingdom.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Unlike migration from other countries, United States migration is not concentrated in specific countries, possibly as a result of the roots of immigration from so many different countries to the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As of 2016, there were approximately 9 million United States citizens living outside of the United States.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] As the result of U.S. tax and financial reporting requirements that apply to non-resident citizens, record numbers of American citizens renounced their U.S. citizenship in the decade from 2010 to 2020.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] In 2024 a new organization was created to lobby the U.S.
[src:david-white-geologist/americans] Congress for relief from citizenship-based taxation that is often cited as the reason for the record renunciations.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] He graduated from Cornell University in 1886, and in 1889 became a member of the United States Geological Survey.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] Eventually, he rose to be chief geologist.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] In 1903 he became an associate curator of paleobotany at the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] He wrote numerous papers on geological and paleontological subjects.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] The David White House, his home for 15 years, is a U.S.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] He made one of the most comprehensive studies on the Glossopteris Flora, the main component of the fossil deposits of mineral coal in Brazil.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] David White was elected to the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1912, and both the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the American Philosophical Society in 1921.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] He won the Thompson Medal in 1931 and the Walcott Medal in 1934.
[src:david-white-geologist/david-white-geologist] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1923.
